Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law establishing administrative liability for violating the time and procedure for payment of goods (work, services) in procurement for State and municipal purposes.
This law is intended to address the very acute problem of the failure of customers to comply with their obligations in public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation of entrepreneurs not being able to obtain payment for government and municipal contracts that had already been executed was widespread.
At the same time, the President of the Russian Federation instructed the Office of the Procurator-General of the Russian Federation to take special control of the problem.
Because the businessmen themselves were unable to deal with unfair customers who entered into unfunded contracts, attempted to evade their obligations to pay and included illegal terms in contracts.
The problem was systemic in general in the country.
Since 2015, 9,700 submissions have been made by the Public Prosecutor ' s Office to protect employers ' rights to pay on public orders, 4,500 officials have been disciplined and 533 administrative officials have been prosecuted, 75 files have been submitted to the investigating authorities for the organization of procedural checks, and 46 of them have been prosecuted.
As a result, more than 66 billion rubles of debt were paid to entrepreneurs.
These huge sums have not been accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multi-billion dollar contracts.
Many, systematic delays in the payment of business services to a much more modest amount have led to basal debts.
Here's a typical case.
The manager of a small company won several million rubles of social transport services.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money in time.
The result is an increasing financial coma of debts on salaries, taxes, loans that would have led to bankruptcy had the entrepreneur not requested assistance from the Public Prosecutor's Office.
The problem has now been as low as possible in a number of regions.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total debt on State and municipal contracts identified by the procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation was about 27.4 billion roubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical levels, the Public Prosecutor ' s Office operates under manual crisis management.
The Attorney-General personally holds visiting meetings with the local authorities, in which all violations discovered by prosecutors are examined in detail and measures taken to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already taken place in Yaroslavla and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal Act No. 189-FZ on amendments to the Code of Administrative Offences, which the President of the Russian Federation signed last week, will be able to improve the payment discipline of public customers in order to establish the administrative liability of officials of the employer for violating the time and procedure for the payment of goods (work, services) in the procurement of State and municipal needs.
The draft law was drafted by the Ministry of Economic Development of the Russian Federation on the initiative of the Office of the Procurator-General.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 roubles for violation by an official of the time limit and of the procedure for payment of goods, works and services in State and municipal procurement.
If an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he is subject to disqualification for a period of one to two years.
All procurators of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure that these legislative innovations are applied in practice.
Civil Rights Unit issued a warning on moving to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to coloured people travelling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads as follows: "The warning to travelers of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, valid until 28 August 2017, calls on African-American travelers, guests and citizens of Missouri to be particularly attentive and cautious when travelling across the state in connection with a number of questionable racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are brought here."
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the group ' s recent Missouri law, which made it more difficult for people to win discriminatory claims, and the fact that State law enforcement agencies disproportionately target minorities.
"You have human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed," told the newspaper Kansas City Old, Rod Chapel, President of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored People of Missouri.
"We hear complaints more often than ever before."
This is the first warning of this kind issued by the organization to the U.S. state.
The Group referred to incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at Missouri University and the death of 20-year-old Tori Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas on a state trip, and Missouri state police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also refers to a recent report by the Office of the Attorney-General of Missouri that black drivers are 75 per cent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri," said Chapel.
"People must be prepared in one way or another whether they will take the money with them for bail or inform their relatives that they are travelling through the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI hate crime reporting programme, there were 100 hate crimes recorded in Missouri in 2015, which makes the state the sixteenth state in terms of the number of hate crimes.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri State Act, which will make it more difficult to bring a case against a legal person for housing or labour discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had issued warnings to travellers in Texas and Arizona after the States had passed new immigration control laws requiring local law enforcement authorities to arrest people for immigration offences, which ACLU believed should have increased the number of racial inspections.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the Department of State for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
