Blocking critics on Facebook: You don't have to run for public office if you're not ready to listen to criticism from voters.
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he didn't shut his critics up.
Because as early as 1783, Washington said, "It is possible to take away the freedom of speech of us deaf and dumb as sheep to slaughter."
Now I'm going to go to Governor Larry Hogan of Maryland, who should have tried to be more Washington-like.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased the posts of at least 450 people who gave their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "what"?
"It's just Facebook," a lot of people will say.
But it's important, too.
And it's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's an amazingly popular Republican governor in a state-prevalent democratic state.
He's second in the approval rating among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan's not a high-end reactionary.
He has demonstrated a strong hand in state management and commitment to his principles.
He also uses Facebook as an easy way to communicate with his voters and to joke about his bald head after chemotherapy.
It is therefore unnecessary and ultimately harmful to block the people who come to the Governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and administered by the administration for taxpayers' money.
In an interview with the Washington Post, press secretary Amelia Ches defended the Governor's actions, claiming that blocking comments was merely their modernization.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spamers, and haters on the Internet.
The Post talked to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are the real people, not trolls, the teacher, the businessman, the pastor, who turn to their elected leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, meaningful, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to Hogan as a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the section of the commentary on the article in Post.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same subject, some say right away that it's a so-called crank, instead of admitting that they're dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens."
What subordinate governors call a concentrated spam attack, others would probably call an "active life stance."
In the Facebook era, it is easy to edit your image simply by blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is a much less dusty job than before when it required sending people, collecting and burning critical newspapers, or arresting and shutting up protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening right now, just in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not listening to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who were banned on his Twitter account.
One of the first, landmark decisions on this subject was taken this week in Virginia.
According to the U.S. District Judge of Alexandria, James K. Kasheris, the chairman of the County Review Board of Laudon violated the First Amendment by banning the voter in her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, the Republican Governor, Matt Bavin, filed a complaint against the American Civil Liberties Union for his behaviour on Facebook and Twitter.
It mustn't be that hard.
In the time of Washington, D.C., the era of affordable postal expenditures was about the same as today's Internet coup.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous letters severely undermined its authority.
And even then Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the aliases "Yuricola," "Valerius," "Belizarius" and "Porcious" wrote letters to newspapers that ridiculed Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington Documents online project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation.
But he wasn't trying to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very heart of our nation.
True leadership means accepting it.
