Of course, working late may be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one decides to walk in the village after five nights," she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a questionable referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, raising their hands in public in front of the occupying forces.
The ongoing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta Government, which retains strict control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was formally divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent State of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as an abandoned city; the road includes an hour-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapura, the provincial administrative centre, to Nabira, and then a five-hour quake on a hired car.
