Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28 per cent of its population living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran, a Phoenix-based company, is only 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province about the size of New Jersey, where 153,000 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced some $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can boast forests valued at $78 billion.
This wealth, however, brings with it one misfortune for the popes, guaranteeing that Indonesia's powerful armed forces retain their suffocating presence here.
According to the New York Times investigation in 2005, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands of greater autonomy on the part of the popes threaten the existence of this gold mine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
Human rights defenders claimed that more than 500,000 papuas had been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more had been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything," a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane diocese, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture - particularly, as alleged in another report, rape and electric shocks - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of casualties because accidents happen every week," says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The Guyanas have been protracted as Papua's resources have attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province ' s 3.5 million population is 83 per cent Christian, but the demographics change as Muslim economic migrants from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive.
Javan shops, barungi, sell fried chicken and a mixture of gado-gado vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to withstand competition.
"Migrants have begun to sell chicken and vegetables cheaper than Papuan natives," explains Abette Yo, a twenty-four-year-old Paniai who moved to Jayapuru, the provincial capital, because of work.
"As a result, Papuan natives - Mama Mother (Women) of Papua - lost their market."
Indonesia's President, Joko Widodo, known as Jokovi, vowed to address inequalities and rights violations in Papua during his presidential campaign in 2014.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter received support from 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But there has been little change in Papua, and locals feel loyal.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, waiting for him to meet our hopes for justice," said Yo.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration of Jokovi Paniai, he experienced a tragedy.
On 7 December 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing Christmas anthems at the Enarotali campfire when two Indonesian soldiers broke out of the dark on a motorcycle.
The scared kids told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javed Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers some time later.
According to the victims and witnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beaten them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Eimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election commission building, and the next day, the situation got worse.
About a thousand papuas men, women and children gathered in a football field in front of the local police station and the military command centre to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed white, the dance of the Papuas tribe of mee pago, running around in circles and playing bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation escalated, the soldiers were given an order by internal radio, saying, "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," as he claimed in an official document that was seen by TIME correspondents, but which was not published in the local media.
50 - year - old Heremias Kayame, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to disperse from house to house.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned around, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist," he told "TIME" magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayama still doesn't know who shot him, but says the bullet came from the front of the soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were lots of shots," he adds.
A local resident, Alfius Jowa, was hit three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, says.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," darkly told the magazine "TIME" Johannes, which, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
"I saw him dead... I kissed him."
General Yotje Mende, Chief Police Inspector of Papua, told reporters that his officers were just "defending" their base because she was being attacked.
"We must defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," stated Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistiyo in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
News of the murders only got to Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovi gave a passionate speech in Jayapur, expressing condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the historical abuse of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Viranto said that he would establish a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But the excuses came almost immediately.
"The majority of violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the nineties or at the beginning of the zeros.
The point is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed," he said.
Viranto then declined to speak with the magazine "TIME" on 5 June in Jakarta and said that he had no plans to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "Everything will be decided through the courts."
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" for the loss of more than 1,000 lives during the 1999 bloody East Timorese independence vote, said that 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai have met similar statements with dark mistrust.
"I've been questioned four times over the last three years, but there has been no change at all," says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid I'm going to be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'm going to be shot."
His brother Jacobus also expressed the view that the people of Paniai were afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came after me," he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in the district of Deiay next to Paniai.
