"We were in such a panic, we're afraid of retaliation," reported 20-year-old Dominggu Badya, who lives near the hospital and sees the wounded being rushed to the hospital.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be held accountable and that the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the region.
Paniai has always been a sick spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is causing dissatisfaction among the tribes of mee, moni, Dani and Damal, scattered throughout the green central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Papua Free Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of the Papuas through sporadic attacks and kidnappings against Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top leaders of OPM come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a response in recent years, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military under the pretext of "protection of national independence."
