The isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudie and Basile Longshan were deported from Papua for "inconsistencies with relevant organizations" despite being given rare permits to film.
According to Felim Keene, Deputy Director for Asia, Human Rights Watch, promises made during Jocovi's campaign to lift restrictions on media work in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebel eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua, face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Government of Indonesia is largely limited to Papua ' s immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific States - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - requested the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including shooting at Paniai.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
A spokesman for the Indonesian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Arramanatha Nasir, waved the group's statement, informing journalists in Jakarta that "Indonesia is still democratic and has a free press, so it would be difficult to conceal evidence of human rights violations."
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
