In Indonesia, new presidential elections will take place in 2019, but the popes say that they are unlikely to vote again for Jokovi.
"Jokovi is a man with good intentions, but he's surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting," says Gobai, president of the tribal council.
He wants Jokovi to know that the people of Paniai, apart from living in the shadow of threats from the greedy army, are trapped in poverty, and their education and health care are miserable.
Gobai says the people of Paniai, like the other papuas, consider their vote for Jokowi to be a duty that he must pay.
"They don't need money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai carried out the latest symbolic act of disobedience: the body of one of the victims was buried on a plot of land in front of the police and military station.
