71-year-old Brooks is a former member of Georgia's Congress who's been fighting for human rights all his life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been corrected.
"We want investigation, we want completion, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice," he says.
"We cannot move on to healing and reconciliation until justice is achieved."
The coroner covers one of Morse Ford's lynching victims with a sheet on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI records received by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighbouring counties were suspected of involvement in lynching.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights defenders say that the city has always been well aware of two related vigilante motives: politics and sex.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court ruled for the first time that black citizens had been allowed to vote for the primer, which was due to take place that summer.
During the same election, according to the FBI, a black user, Roger Malcolm, stabbed Barnett Hester in a fight, a white landowner, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says the rumors are that Hester was sleeping with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the baby she was supposed to have wasn't from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But when they drove out of prison and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a crowd of vigilantes surrounded the car.
"It turns out that he organized and commanded Harrison's murders," one of the reports of the FBI concludes.
"It is also clear that there was an agreement between state and city law enforcement agencies, which not only took part in the murders, but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identity of witnesses."
Brooks calls it shorter.
"It was an attempt on voting rights," he says.
"They've all been killed to send a signal to black people in town, "if you register and vote, you'll have the same thing."
For almost a decade, Cassandra Greene runs an annual play that reproduces the lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visible, it captures the audience and tells of the deep racism that many would like to believe is no longer in America.
It's hard to watch and it's harder to turn away, but Green thinks that's what matters.
"We don't want to talk about Lynch's courts because they show us our own ugliness," she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you if you don't hear me or hear what I've been through."
The rehearsals of this year's play began in June, and on the first day, almost 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest black - gathered in the room and listened to a year-long review of the play.
