He's concerned and embarrassed.
Am I overplaying?
"No," says Greene through the laugh.
"I just don't think the whites said nigga back then."
"Yes, yes," laughs one of the black artists.
"You're gonna call it a hard 'r'."
And the energy in the room is also changing: discomfort is replaced by a sense of partnership.
Everybody has to do the right thing, not just for the play, but for the memory of the four people killed.
The scene starts over.
This time, when Raskona says the "n" word, it's clear and sharp.
No one laughs.
The play ends cruelly and quickly.
Screaming, shooting, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands above the bodies of actors and sings the sad song "Strange Fruit" by Billy Holiday.
Her voice breaks through the word.
In a hundred yards, half a hundred viewers wipe their tears and sweats out of their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show; many live close by.
They all endured Georgia's heavy breath for almost eight hours while Brooks was taking them on a pilgrimage to Malcolm and Dorsey's graves.
Until then, the murders were only a story, but now that they're standing in the same place where people were lynching, it seems like their ghosts are hanging in the air.
When the last note of the song fades, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Kids bend to their heads, touch the blood paint, and still bodies, whisper to each other.
