New results of tests published to assess the age of asylum-seekers in Sweden
Recent tests of asylum-seekers in Sweden who have been subjected to a new method of medical age assessment show that more than 80 per cent of those tested were assessed as over 18 years of age, but not all trust the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) criticized for not being able to determine the real age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensics Agency has now published 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of the testees were rated as 18 years of age or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensics Agency assessed that the test "probably 18 years of age or older."
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was "probably less than 18."
Tests are conducted only in cases where the age of a person is questionable.
According to Johan Geransson of the Forensics Agency, the results are consistent with the results of the past months.
"We don't see a big difference with last month's statistics, the numbers are quite the same," he said to the portal The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which persons were assessed as having reached the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum-seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases "most likely the age of the test is 18 years or older."
However, after considering the 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, a person had openly stated that he was 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which consists of X-raying wisdom teeth and tomography of knee joints and giving them to dentists and X-rays, has also provoked criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is the endocrinologist at the Caroline Institute, Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans to determine whether they have passed through sexual maturity before or after normal maturity.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think we need to use the measurement methods that we use now.
Biological age is thus very uncertain.
If we can't determine it with certainty, we shouldn't pretend to be able to do it," he said to Metro.
However, Geranssen of the Forensics Agency argued in favour of the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of mistaking a child as an adult is small.
We face the greatest risk when the person is 18 soon, in which case he is about 10 percent."
