The President will determine the order and place of the swearing-in.
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law have been drafted by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Building.
A week ago, the deputies planned to determine directly the procedure for swearing in the law.
Children under 18 years of age, as well as disabled persons, will be released from the solemn oath, as follows from the finalized text of the amendments to the Russian Citizenship (Izvesy) Bill, which the Committee will consider before the second reading at its meeting on 11 July.
President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of swearing in Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents on 6 June, during a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
This idea was introduced by the deputies as an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the annulment of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of terrorist or extremist offences: for example, for public incitement to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (art. 205.2, para. 2, of the Criminal Code), as well as for the hijacking of aircraft, trains or water transport, but only if the act is linked to terrorism (art. 211, para. 4).
According to the bill, its logic was that by issuing citizenship documents, a person signed a promise to comply with Russian legislation - by embarking on the path of extremism - he broke that promise.
The bill was introduced in April by the leaders of the Dumian factions, Vladimir Vasilyev (Uni-Russian), Gennady Züganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Just Russia) and the Speaker of the DG Vyacheslav Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies accepted it on first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Building and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but it has now been revised again.
It now states that the President of the Russian Federation will determine the procedure for the swearing-in.
Previously, parliamentarians had intended to describe the procedure directly in the Russian Citizenship Act, stating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the State emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event would take place - the list of places where a Russian coat of arms could be placed is governed by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive authorities, etc.
It could probably be the registry.
A solemn pledge of Russian citizenship will be made once officials have checked their documents.
But a Russian passport will be issued to a person only after the oath of office follows from the finalized text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath must be preceded by the signing of the decree.
The updated text states that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, not from the age of 14.
There is a rule under which persons who are incapable or have limited legal capacity, as well as those who cannot say, read or sign the oath themselves, are released from the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt "others" from this procedure,
The updated draft law also lays down a special procedure for the admission to Russian of Ukrainian citizens who are considered to be Russian speakers.
They will have to formally renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting an application to that effect to the Ukrainian authorized body.
A notarized copy of the application will have to be given to Russian officials.
Renunciation of "other" nationality will not be required, as it is now, if it is provided for in an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons beyond the control of the person."
A group of deputies proposed an amendment to the Act, including the first Vice-Speaker of the DG Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poclonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all "One Russia").
I think many of you know that it's not realistic to get a certificate from Ukraine, just impossible.
Consequently, very many people are waiting for a decision on their fate regarding Russian citizenship, " explained the head of the Thought Committee on State Construction and Legislation, Pavel Krascheninnikov (ER).
In addition, the text made it clear that restrictions on certain positions for foreigners would not apply to those who had given up "other" citizenship in writing and had passed their previous passport to the Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs, but "for reasons beyond their control" he had not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Foreigners are now prohibited from holding positions in the municipal service, from being employed in facilities and organizations whose activities are related to the security of Russia.
Nor can a person with dual citizenship or residence permits of another country become a member of the State Duma or a member of the Council of the Federation.
The law is scheduled to enter into force on 1 September 2017 and the necessary by-laws must be in place by then.
