Judges are offered protection from presidents
On behalf of Vladimir Putin, the Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC) has drawn up proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the court presidents and to introduce their election.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wishes to introduce special districts which will not be linked to the administrative and territorial division of the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential commission.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the council members.
A meeting with the Council on 8 December 2016 discussed, inter alia, isolated cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see 9 December "JS").
The HRC ' s work has resulted in 25 proposals that address both the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court presidents to enhance the independence of the rest of the judiciary.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judiciary, the President of the Court must, in the view of the HRC, submit him for appointment without the right to refuse, as the law now permits.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to allocate cases to the judges.
To do this, to allow experts, may have a specially written computer program.
The HRC also considers that the President is not entitled "to determine the results of the judge's qualification, to initiate disciplinary proceedings against him or her, and to decide on additional financial payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move on to "the election of the judges themselves" and to "reliance their powers for a relatively short period of time, with mandatory rotation."
All presidents of courts (from the Republic to the District) are now appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the President of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes a new organization of appeal and cassation before the courts of general jurisdiction.
Their structure is now linked to the administrative and territorial division of the Russian Federation.
The HRC states that "it is necessary to ensure that individual courts of appeal and cassation are organized not at the level of the regional courts in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts."
The experts are based on the practice of arbitral tribunals.
They have "judicial districts" which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but which thus guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use "telephone law."
HRC suggests that the magistrates should be strengthened by the people's assessors to deal with certain "civil and administrative cases" with them.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement at work, protection of honour and dignity, deprivation of driving rights, etc.
"It's only our proposals," explained SHRC member, Constitutional Court judge retired Tamar Morshakov.
She also recalled that the President ' s mandate had not only been with the HRC, but also with the Supreme Court (HJ), which had not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the SC to carry out the assignment (between the co-implementers, the Office of the Attorney-General and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, Vyacheslav Lebedev, President of the Supreme Court, is due before 1 September.
Living a high life: Semi-tage and sneaky design techniques turned this little apartment in Earl's Court into a large house
Joan Lee, a former banker interested in real estate repair, moved from a large house in Nightsbridge to an apartment in Earl's Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a beautiful, like-like, Queen Anne's house, and in favour of a new design, it says that Joan didn't pack her things and move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Nightsbridge on a much larger square," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earl's Court, and there were these same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price on the same day."
Since the first view, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Initially, it was an apartment with one bedroom of complex design - to get into the bedroom, to go through the kitchen - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and semi-ethage to maximize the benefits from the generous height of the ceiling.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
That was my demand," she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Duck & Shed architectural design studio in Notting Hill to use the 12.5-foot ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project but would be fit for Joan.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-ethage where full growth could be achieved.
Erfan had to think creatively to deal with the brift.
"The work with steel structures is very complicated," he explains.
"We had to arrange the rooms so that they would be one above the other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was not just necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they would be at the right height and allow for the use of space from the top and from the bottom."
This solution allowed Erfan to set up two full rooms one above the other in the space allocated - and many more interesting.
From the semi-tage through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius," the view of the fine living room is at the bottom.
Mirror furniture with gold cutters, silver accents, and vintage lighting devices from Serge Muy set up the design style.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding sight, space and light.
The short corridor is surrounded by mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the mirror shield seems to be a window into the other room.
At the entrance, mirror closets are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a sense of luxury, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
There's nothing new about the kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it's a moving up door, like a garage.
"The engineering art has been involved here," Erfan tells me about the fibre-film-backed wood-film door.
"It's a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slips very easily."
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage facilities, Joan received an additional 16 square metres, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
"In the end, the floor area is exactly what you're gonna sell, that's what your real estate is valued for," says Erfan.
"Bruddenly speaking, the real estate agent will enter and calculate on the basis of the floor space."
Here, they were able to increase the floor area using quality materials that give the space a shade of luxury.
"Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the house," says Erfan.
"No one falls in love with the electrical wiring in the walls.
It's important, but it doesn't hurt the strings of our hearts."
This shows that with a good design and an extended meter, an apartment can turn from something normal to something amazing.
Actually, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
