Paul wants to leave the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still having a violent dispute about the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 objects worth more than half a billion dollars purchased since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew up in a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's list today includes office buildings, construction sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Golden Bank and Mount Buller, and shopping centres in the suburbs.
By agreement with the late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lucis family - owns about two thirds of the company's assets, while Paul owns about one third of the company's assets.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
"The section offered by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best pieces of property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first Supreme Court hearings took place.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which Paul thinks Colin expelled him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of certain facilities.
In Colin's testimony at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes that the dispute will be resolved.
"My Italian roots make me consider my family a top priority," he wrote.
Judicial costs are increasing as a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, e-mails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer are added to the case; both parties have attracted the best known lawyers, including the Crown Counsel of Allan Myers, and the best cookers.
Mrs. De Lutís and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s, they have been running milk bars and gastrons, and in the early 1970s they bought a shop in Brunswick.
With financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the final years of school, and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old) " at the time.
Anna De Lutís says that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, were hoping to transfer their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Louigi often told me he didn't want the brothers to judge," she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of De Lutis' group of companies; Colina says that Mark received 10 million when he left business and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "unsatisfied with the financial terms of their branch."
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL Board of Directors and, according to the 2015 biography of Eddie McGeere, the best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied with a text message stating that, since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing to say."
"I'm very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and talk about the name of our family in court," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a statement that he was trying to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father wouldn't want to see me and Paul arguing in court," he said, adding that "still hoping for a solution to the conflict."
On Friday, that hope seemed to have receded.
"Our case is about to be judged," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff is planning to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really do it.
