Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their subpoena by giving Trump material - reliable or not - that confirms their views.
"Politico," just to that story, wrote in May about the tendency of the advisors to constantly give the president questionable information.
Here is one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Trump's current and former employees say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who's behind them.
That was the case at the end of February, when someone handed the president a printout of an article with GotNews.com, the website of Charles C. Johnson's Internet Provocateur, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Welsch was accused of "sitting behind a leak" in the White House.
