These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
The Tumen Public Prosecutor ' s Office is fighting against an HIV dissident.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office challenged the ruling of the Kalininsky District Court of Tumen, which terminated criminal proceedings against a local resident whose daughter died of HIV.
As a result, the child is said to have died because the mother is HIV-dissenting and has refused treatment.
However, the court acquitted her of her responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the father concerned.
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished in order not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against the resident of Tumen was brought under article 109, paragraph 1, of the Criminal Code (cause of death by negligence), in April, after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection 4B.
According to the Public Prosecutor ' s Office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that there was no HIV infection," explained the Prosecutor's Office in Tumen province.
The criminal case was filed with the Kalininsky District Court of Tumen, which decided to terminate it on 25 July.
The deceased girl's father made a request to do so, explaining that "he has forgiven his wife, has no claim against her, has made amends and has apologized."
The Public Prosecutor ' s Office disagreed with the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be revoked and re-examined.
The girl died, and the harm caused by the crime cannot be repaired.
The HIV-positive mother, contrary to the doctors' recommendations, refused to examine the baby and treat her with a dangerous infection," reported the prosecutor's press office.
According to the Supervisory Authority, she should be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents would follow her example.
According to the Tumen AIDS Centre, some 12 children living with HIV are currently not receiving medical care due to parental refusal in the Tumen region.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of the special group's work, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV changed their opinion - allowed diagnosis, started taking drugs," said the AIDS Centre's spokesperson, Elena Loseva.
She said that it was not possible to legally influence parents, and not all HIV-positive children were detected as a result - mothers were not allowed to examine them, were hiding, and were fleeing with children from hospitals.
What are the risks of HIV dissidents?
At the end of last year, Petersburg sociologists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called movement of HIV dissidents.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Health professionals and AIDS activists of the service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and their spread is seen as a serious threat.
