The angry residents attacked the municipality of Solihall, saying that he was "incompetent to solve the problem."
An anonymous local woman said, "They came here on Monday night after being driven from Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by."
The municipality should be shamed and forced to act because it is unable to solve the problem.
The Gypsy were here in May, they were chased away, and they came back again.
Last night, more gypsies arrived, and today perhaps more.
"The municipality of Birmingham knows how to solve this problem, they get long-term court orders to protect their parks," she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don't like that I keep paying the municipal tax, and the municipality can't even put an end to it."
A local resident who wanted to remain anonymous said, "This is ridiculous, we just saw these gypsies leave the previous time, and this attack continues, please."
This time, there's more of them, and we've even seen a horse come to the meadow."
The representative of the municipality of Solihalla said: "We know about the illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and cooperate with the Solihall police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them away as soon as possible."
To help us collect evidence, it is essential that as many locals as possible report any anti-social or criminal behaviour to the police by telephone 101.
This gives us an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
