Italy is tightening the tone against the ships of NGOs saving migrants.
Italy warned NGOs owned by rescue vessels in the Mediterranean Sea that they would not be able to continue their work unless they complied with the new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," said Home Minister Mario Minniti in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
Minniti's warning was issued the day after the Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rette on suspicion that his crew actually cooperated with traffickers and facilitated illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had been working for only one year, had rejected comments on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Cartozio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we very much regret that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone now," says the organization's social media statement.
"We will only be able to assess all the charges now, after we gather all the information and can assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventa belonging to Jugend Rette since October.
His crew is suspected of taking migrants on board with lifeboats that traffickers sent directly to them and allowing smugglers to leave with boats that they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place only 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, as alleged by the prosecution, whose contents were published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the zone, more from humanitarian zeal than from any other motive.
The Code of Conduct requires mainly that courts of the Juventure type will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, Maltese MOAS, and Pro-Activa Open hugs from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable, provided that they did not cause any "significant change or interference" in its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Médecins sans frontières (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said that the sharp decline in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations in recent weeks indicated that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors were bearing fruit.
"In the last few days, we began to see the light at the end of the tunnel," said the minister.
He announced plans for further negotiations with the Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
