The Russian Federation authorities have recently significantly intensified their policies on the Libyan track and, with visits to Moscow, delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have been involved.
The head of the Russian contact group on the internal Lebanese settlement under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, the assistant head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Dongov, described the objectives of Moscow in the region and on whom he was betting.
The contact group on Libya that you are chairing is hardly known.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here, there's a veil of mystery.
What exactly do you do, what are your goals?
The Contact Group was established on the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Her activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Dums' deputy from Chechnya).
The latter is authorized to work in Libya as Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Volodin.
The formation of the group was prompted by the detention in Libya of a Russian tanker, Mechanik Chebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 persons on board).
We've been thinking about how to help the crew.
At that time, a contact group was formed from military experts, representatives of the State Duma, and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How come you're the one who led her?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the team.
Our activities were not limited to the release of seafarers from the Chebotarev Mechanica.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the United Nations-recognized government led by Faiz Saraj is based) and from Tobruk (a parliamentary seat that opposes the Government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya.
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Libya Vice Prime Minister), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian seafarers.
At that time, it was agreed that a contact group should be established to make better use of these contacts.
Its mission is to analyse the situation, identify key factors and players, and to engage in dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I would like to stress in particular that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict; we are engaged in dialogue with all of us.
How many are in the contact group and how many are in Libya?
There are now five members of the contact group.
Among them are people with experience in the security sector, including the Ministry of Defence.
We also wish to include in the team of specialists on the region, representatives of the Institute of the Middle East of the RAN.
No one of our staff is in Libya on a permanent basis, and that is not necessary.
Are there Russian military advisers, instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group has ex-military members...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities closed to a certain point, such as Misrata (where militias are based, which played a role in overthrowing Libyan leader Muammar Qadhafi in 2011 and have increased markedly in the years to come).
We arrived in Misrata in January this year.
We were scared, said it was all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation on our own, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what the rumors are, what is really the role of Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the units that were involved in the destruction of the IG in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was taken away from members of the banned "Islamic State" in Russia.
We wanted to look at them, to meet these people, to verify that they were the ones who played a crucial role in the destruction of IH in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed it to himself.
And what's your conclusion?
The Islamic State won not Haftar in Libya?
He didn't do it.
Haftar was operating on another front in Benghazi.
And the IG in Sirte fought the structures that were under the authority of the government in Tripoli.
And by the way, we invited the people who carried out this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they came - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, and the Libyan delegation was received by the Federation Council, the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Rosgwardia.
You are, as we understand it, in all of the Libyan regions, and you are probably imagining the moods of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think that it will be possible to implement the ceasefire, the elections that took place in late July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, agreements will be broken down, hostilities will resume, the parties will attempt to seize power alone?
For us, the fact that Saraj and Haftar had agreed to another meeting was a good signal, not so long ago, that was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
And as for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftara, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was on board the Russian carrier Admiral Kuznetsov that day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata, they didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people who came to us today."
But our challenge is to show that we do not support only Haftara, we are engaged in dialogue with all the key parties to the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar were in touch.
Does understanding with Russian partners at the human, emotional level make it easier for him to study twice in the USSR?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
He's Russian if he knows, he's very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us certainly facilitates dialogue with him.
And by the way, it's not just him.
When we talk to the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian perfectly.
And they reach out to Russia, they're kind of nostalgic about it.
Do you consider it likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will be lifted as soon as possible?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Of course we are, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and do not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be on an equal footing.
With regard to the arms embargo, there are constant calls from Libyans for Russia to contribute in some way to its lifting.
The constitution-making process is well under way in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then the elections are to be held, as was said at Saraj and Haftara's meeting.
If elections are held and legitimate authority is finally elected (and none of the parties now has such a status), it is possible to raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the United Nations.
It is pointless and dangerous to raise this issue now, which will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, felt abandoned by EU allies.
Could Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the option that Haftara's troops will take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
It's a very timely question.
We're actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow has a dialogue with both Haftar and Saraj and Misurata and the south of the country.
In this regard, the tribes in southern Libya play a major role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the southerns stopping the flow of migrants in the distant fields?
So, technically speaking, they're turning back the buses that Nigerian migrants are taking?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help bring the southerners together in the negotiations between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see the unity of opinion between Haftar and Saraj on this issue.
The head of Government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered to be an Islamist who advocates the introduction of sharia law in the country.
How radical is he?
Would that not stand in the way of a relationship with Russia or the West?
I'll give my personal opinion of him.
In my view, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but it is its own position that Libya must be a fully normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he's also actively fighting terrorists.
Where did he get that reputation?
It was created by those countries that were not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is a capital, with legislative, executive and judicial powers.
There's a national oil corporation, a national bank and other government structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
And we mixed all their cards and started to communicate actively with both Tripoli and Tobrook.
And we are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with Libya's state-owned oil company, NOC.
The NOC director, Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosnefti Igor Sechin made a deal, came directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, there was the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess I'll resell it.
What other economic interests do Russia have in Libya?
In plans to re-sign the contracts entered into at Muammar Qadhafi.
These include previous transport agreements (rail construction), energy (electrication) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
So, as with Iran, this is a "oil-for-service" scheme?
I don't know what the scheme is, I don't deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the most important thing.
We're actually doing peacekeeping there.
What is important for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans reach an agreement so that they can establish order and that Libya will no longer be an enabling environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, that is the main task - helping the Libyan people and pushing terrorists out of there.
Do you have any information on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical fighters from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to clarify this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee who said that to date there are no Russians and other countries of the former USSR.
He said that he had about 50,000 telephone records of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya) and that the Russian speech did not sound there.
What states are these militants from?
I wouldn't want to go into that.
Then let's put the question differently.
How many of the Islamist fighters in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are almost no Libyans, no more than 5%.
The rest of them are foreign.
Could Moscow hold an intra-Livian negotiation like Paris?
There are plans like that.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow and have indicated their readiness to come back to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such a negotiation take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits are yet to take place, and I hope that there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
