Sent by Michelle Carter for reports that led to Conrad Roy's suicide.
The Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years' imprisonment for having encouraged her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide by means of text messages and telephone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months behind bars and five more years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday, "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers stated that she and Roy both suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the judgment standing, with her hands tied and her eyes lowered.
"In her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor stated to the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She didn't accept responsibility," she said.
"She didn't show remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monice said that, in his view, her "age, maturity or even mental illness did not have a visible impact on her actions."
The Prosecutor read the statements of Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, saying, "It has not been a day since I mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I'm doing - I'm trying to support his sisters despite all the pain that's gonna stay with us forever," he says.
Roy Camdin Roy's sister said that she was constantly haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"Lying to a man who's always been with me since I was born is a pain that stays with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as Massachusetts does not have a law that would hold a person responsible for advising him to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he had been pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know if there are many ways," she wrote in a few messages sent two weeks before his death while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she killed herself, she said, "You have to do this, Conrad," and "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you're gonna be free and happy."
Judge Monice said that Carter wanted attention by means of Roy's death, and forbade her to communicate with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The views of the legal profession on this matter were divided.
One of the few protecting Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of killing her British flatmate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, a 30-year-old, published his separate opinion in the Los Angeles Times, saying, "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
