Audi to be modified to 850,000 diesel vehicles
The day before the Audi announcement, BMW announced that it would offer software upgrades in over 350,000 vehicles.
The Chairman of BMW stated that the company believed that "there were more intelligent ways than driving restrictions," with reference to European cities - including Munich, where BMW was located - that were considering the possibility of prohibiting or restricting the use of diesel cars.
Daimler announced on Thursday that he is modifying three million Mercedes cars in Europe to reduce their diesel exhaust.
None of the companies called their move a review.
European automobile manufacturers actively promoted the use of diesel cars in Europe and the United States to promote compliance with carbon dioxide emission regulations.
But nitrogen oxides that emit diesel engines are considered carcinogens and can cause asthma.
The cost to vehicle manufacturers of equipment neutralizing diesel vehicles is also rising and it is difficult to maintain a competitive price for cars.
While German car manufacturers are under close scrutiny, Chancellor Angela Merkel's government has also been accused of condoning powerful automobile manufacturers and ignoring signs of a problem.
Companies try not to repeat the mistakes of Volkswagen, which masked the use of so-called "flood devices," which during testing could correct the amount of harmful gases emitted to conform to the rules and were shut down under normal driving conditions.
In the United States, several leaders of Volkswagen were convicted and the rest are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
