Astronomers found a "Hell" planet where even iron can melt.
For the first time, after studying the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, the astrophysicists were surprised by its temperature, which was able to evaporate iron and other metals.
Experts noticed that water molecules are so heated by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble telescope captured the glowing water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature makes the planet's atmosphere glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to the so-called hot jupiters - gas giants, which are comparable in size and mass to the largest planet of the solar system but which are dozens of times closer to the parent star.
This year's exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "earth" days, and its gas envelope is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and South France, but there are now concerns that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavanda has grown worse because of dry weather and disease-borne insects; this has caused the constant headache of scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Ches, an expert at the CREPPAM Agricultural Research Institute in Provence, says: "Lavanda in Provence is indeed at risk, because in recent years this plant has been affected by the effects of climate change: in the spring and especially in the autumn, the rains have become much smaller.
It affects the life span of the lavender.
And there are also small cicades that jump on the leaves of insects carrying micro-bacteriums; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavand is not only attracted to vacationers; lavender oil is very useful in perfume and cosmetics.
Eric Ches says, "Instead of very long ears with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or absent.
So we have fewer parts that contain ether oil."
The solutions currently under consideration included improving water distribution and reducing evaporation from soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water, and producing more drought-resistant varieties.
