It's a resemblance: an artist makes portraits using Chelsea Manning DNA.
At the center of the hall in Friedman Gallery in New York City, people's faces are hanging from the ceiling on the wire - white, black, and brown - all of which are elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were made by Heather Dewey-Harborg, an artist, of cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Levenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving 35 years for the famous broadcast of confidential diplomatic telegrams on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is called "The Resurrection of Similarity."
It's the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey Harborg, whose art unites technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transsexual woman and a famous dissident, whom Barack Obama reduced the sentence just three days before the end of her presidency.
By analysing through a computer program the DNA obtained from Manning and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of persons who might have had such a genome, Dewey Harborg created a profound, though difficult, manifesto on not only the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the ingerent determinism of these interpretations - but also the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward, but from her teens, openly said she thought she was a woman, was sentenced to 20 episodes in 2013, including six violations of the Spy Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her pictures in prison were not available, so only one picture of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, where Manning was wearing a platinum wig, apparently embarrassingly, while driving a car; she was associated with that photograph.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed his 2012 vision of strangers project.
In it, the artist created pictures of unknown people with forensic evidence such as butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from it and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," explained Dewey-Hagborg at a preliminary screening of a new press exhibit.
At that time, Chelsea could not be seen and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait made of her DNA.
In such an unusual way, the artist and her muse in prison became pen pals and exchanged letters for two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Destructed Images," illustrated by Shoily Kanungo, who illustrated how the president would ease Chelsea's punishment in the future and she would be able to visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama actually decided to release Manning only a few days after the release of the book turned out to be a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something deep and strong about the exhibition opening right now, when Donald Trump announces war to people who reveal classified information in the government, and invents new ways to create on Twitter a feud that he's supposed to mitigate.
When Dewey Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all of this over time, she said that "nothing happens by accident."
In a statement by an artist written on the wall of the gallery, Manning's huge signature downstairs (with a heart instead of a point above "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic division based on sex, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of pencil C, G and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as a scientific artist has done), Dewey Harborg hoped to show how we all look amazingly similar, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn't define what we are, how open genetic data are for interpretation, and how subjective it is," said Dewey Harborg; her 2007 video work, "Lange Memories," is also posted here.
"D.N.A. can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of the exhibition in the same room is the above-mentioned novel in the comics.
In it, the King Kong Manning appears above the U.S. Correctional Czar with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they will win," it says.
"So don't ever shut up."
"This is a direct quote from the letter she wrote to me," says the artist welcoming us from Philadelphia.
"I still have the creeps when I'm talking about it."
Manning hasn't seen the exhibition personally yet - as visualized in the comics - but when it arrives, she'll be welcomed by masks in the middle of the room, her own genomic simulaks gathered as crowds of protesters.
It's also done intentionally, just like everyone on the exhibition up to height (5"2, height Manning), where a pencil was painted with a genetic gapl group.
"I'd put them on the walls earlier, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people," Dewey Harborg says about portraits.
"I wanted them to look like a mass movement that was formed around Chelsea as a movement that was also behind her liberation."
