Startups that will help your company not become another Uber.
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among his e-commerce start-up staff, but the polls weren't working.
The answers were often vague, useless or, worse, insincere.
Even though she promised anonymity, some staff members did not trust the process.
"He has never been consistent and objective," said Errett, who runs a 75-person company called Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, engaged in electronic trading in hair care.
She therefore sought the help of third parties.
A new type of personnel start-up is emerging to help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software that is designed to measure employee involvement, they allow companies to conduct rapid interviews, to contact certain teams and demographic groups, to offer staff anonymity and hotlines for complaints and, in some cases, to allow informants to pass the top management and direct contact with the Directorate.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit to monitor health, and where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Glint startup from Redwood City, whose analysis programs are used by companies to measure employee involvement.
Errett told me that she's gained a better understanding of what her staff think and feel in three years of using Glint.
In addition to the rapid surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in a visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are slightly aware that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber who was caught up in a scandal when a former employee posted a post on a blog that described the aggressive environment in which those who complained were punished.
For startups like "Glint," it's a desire to control the situation - an opportunity for profitable businesses.
The Internet portal Let's Talk About Pay, which is dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry may cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The "Convercent" launch from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behaviour, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year against the backdrop of a decline in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently appeared among clients.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send individually commissioned staff opinions, collect confidential real-time responses, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows staff to report bad behaviour.
And if the top manager is involved, the complaints go straight to the department.
"The Court of Public Opinion seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
Quinlan reported that if it was found that the company was ill-treating employees or was unethical, even if the inspectors did not intervene, the company might face costly consequences in the form of client boycotts, staff departures and lawsuits.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 institutions, has been using Convercent for over a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and to propose a simple way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if a staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a telephone number or head office e-mail, file an official complaint and hope that she would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, reported by James Vitrano, the head of the legal department of Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no normal way to follow up on employees' complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, haracement and unfair pay - can be quickly discovered and addressed.
"I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the staff situation," said Vitrano, who runs the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Quinland, companies began to take employees' ethics, values and involvement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen's accounting firm collapsed due to ethical irregularities caused by Dela Enron.
But it was only when "social media spread massively" that companies realized that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from spreading virally online.
" Before starting using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies for their products on a regular basis.
It's a business model and an opportunity that has won the approval of venture capital investors who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
"Glint" received $10 million in November from "Bessemer Venture Partners," bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, cultures and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today's employees expect more jobs than they did before.
In markets with hard competition, such as the Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, it is only a necessary minimum.
The employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they are devoting their time to companies with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work in a company, they feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do produces results, they try more to make such a company successful," says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both "Convercent" and "Glint" are used.
Investors earn income when companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies do well when employees are loyal and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase staff commitment and involvement, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to cultural experts in the workplace, it is important to have data on staff involvement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if the company asks employees for feedback, it might give the impression that change is coming.
And if change does not occur quickly enough or at all, frustration may develop and staff will lose interest.
"If you're gonna ask for 4,000 offers, you should be ready to have 4,000 interviews," says Russell Rat, the president of the management consulting firm at Kotter International, who had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
'Cause if you don't go all the way, the staff will be wondering, "Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly interviews with employees, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports the problem with Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees who were unhappy with decision-making speed and communication quality, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge of its employees and hopes that in the long term this knowledge will help it to better retain employees in an industry known for its high turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you'll lose people," said Vitrano.
If you lose people, you lose clients.
And if you lose clients, you lose companies.
