Create a novel comic: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeese," and in the 1970s and 1980s it was a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But for 700 years from his cozy place in the Bühl Valley in Kent County, he was watching a violent story around him, and now he's inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire with coke hair and a tendency to historical documents, to a novel comic.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel that way in person when you hold this letter in your hand."
The castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwards and describes the families who lived in Scotty; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists Isaac Lenkevich, Broney May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote "Dead Man's Tooths and Other History," a collection of British Library documents; this project suddenly touched him deeply.
"I could've just gotten a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites," he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those days they lit fire.
And in 300 years, in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
Oh, I love archives!"
For a man so passionate about old papers, to get support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and live in the castle for four months (to be honest, I've been a little bit in there) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the Victorian "new" castle, going through the archives, and looking at the many treasures of the estate and old things - such as the heads of hyenas on walls or bottles that have been lying in the mouth for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, spoke to foresters, gardeners, and sometimes with artists working on illustrations to his book.
Then at night, he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
Scotty's castle history is not very well understood because the National Foundation only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassey, died.
When Rhodes arrived there ten years later, the staff had just begun to deal with the archive, which he described as "the things that the aristocrats had been in the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what you thought was boring, says Rhodes, but two families fought for this birch.
It happens, you guys!"
In some of the stories of the castle collection, it is becoming the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in the Workman, the hero is leaving the castle that has just been built to join the 1381 Peasant Revolution.
"There is evidence of a riot that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called "Kent and Sussex's Knightly Families," Rhodes says.
"The Crestian uprising began in these places, and I thought the riot was a fitting beginning.
Maybe they were connected?"
Other stories are closely related to the castle's history, such as the Holy One, which describes a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the British Reformation.
Or "Contrabandist," about an 18th-century smuggler, Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (which was discovered several years later when the coffin was dug).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family of all the people Scotty had: "The gentlemen seemed to be a perfect cheat, always in debt and spending money on something they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I imagine them as a company of cute guys who are able to care for big estate heirs."
After finishing his job at Rhodes Castle, he looks for other opportunities to gain unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish interior, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elamyanmäki, a place where a sanatorium was in the early 20th century, and then it was regrown by the forest.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: damn it, I have to go back to real life."
