Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help to make the CDC easier.
Red meat and chocolate are usually considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate the symptoms of those suffering from inflammable intestinal diseases.
It is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 3000 in the United Kingdom, leading to colic and abdominal swelling, chronic or bloody diarrhea, loss of weight, and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of triptophan protein contributes to the production of immune cells that increase the tolerance of the intestines.
The leading researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that the immune cells in the intestine ensured that harmful germs from food did not enter the body.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammation process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance by protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too heavily affected by inflammation, it can lead to inflammable intestinal diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacteria in their intestines have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria need a triptophane -- one of the building elements of protein -- to trigger the emergence of these cells.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a link between one type of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of a normal intestine microbioma, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was kept in the diet of mice, the more these immunized cells they had."
He suggested that people would work the same way: a combination of L. reuteri and a rich tryptophane diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammable intestinal environment.
The postcard, Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganas, studying a variety of tolerant immune cells, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the microbioms of the intestine of mice - the communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the cells in the intestine of mice was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but missing in mice without them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that had no good microbioma and did not develop this type of immune cell were given L. reuteri, and immunized cells appeared in them.
In order to understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers raised L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transported small portions of the liquid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells separated from mice.
The immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of triptofane, known as indol-3-molecular acid.
When researchers doubled the number of triptophenes in mice, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of triptophones was halved, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that people have the same tolerance cell as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our intestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of the L. reuteri triptophane contribute to the growth of cells in humans as in mice, but in humans suffering from inflammable intestinal diseases, defects were found in the triptofane genes.
She says, "Perhaps the development of these cells needs to be strengthened, because the inflammation processes on the inside surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of triptophane with L. reuteri are potentially likely to increase their population."
