The White House requisition cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to bring a marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One," when the president is on board, became the centrepiece of a White House event on July 17, where American construction programs were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pens and senior White House officials examined technological products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was set up next to a yacht from Maine State, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a pick-up truck from Mississippi.
According to the first Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the helicopter control department, the White House Military Department ordered the helicopter to be present in a private order, or "FRAGO," just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of the "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to know that you're aware because it's an unusual, widely publicized event," wrote HMX-1 Commander in an e-mail to his superior, the Deputy Chief of Aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at around 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return the flight in accordance with working hours restrictions.
The first crew escorted the helicopter during the event, while the unit ' s security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by TIME whether a second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the activity was in conflict with the regulation.
"We asked, among other things, if this wasn't a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that it wasn't," the commander wrote.
"It looks like you have nowhere to go," said the deputy chief.
The event "Done in America" was announced by the White House as an official event and was not covered by Hatch's law.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the reform of the health sector, which was being drafted in the Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's the only thing that's unusual to ask for a photo opportunism.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is thrilled to see "Done in America," where 50-state products made by American workers from American materials were presented," said the deputy White House spokesperson, Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often conduct training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House to the nearest inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight for the "America Made" event was counted to the crew on the basis of the required training flights in a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of "non-presidential support tasks."
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
Sikorsky reported that Sikorsky did not participate in the organization of a helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's 2017 fiscal year clock, the Department of Defense's VH-3D rate is $24,380 per hour.
The unit ' s records indicate that the flight time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield based at the Quantico Marine Air Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
"It's totally wrong to calculate the value for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement," Walters says.
"These indicative rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations."
According to a study carried out by RAND in 2015, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but indeed take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At that time, Sean Spicer, a former White House spokesperson, spoke out to defend the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to show things done in America this week," said Spycer.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
It is therefore, of course, entirely appropriate to draw attention to this."
It was unclear whether Trump had interacted with the helicopter by looking at the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver's seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky, making a press joke about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the president. "I have three."
