There will be two new territories in Russia that are ahead of social and economic development: Abaza and Novotroitsk.
The relevant decisions of the Government of the Russian Federation will enter into force today, 4 August.
The boundaries and economic activities of the TOR have been defined in the territory of the city of Abaza in the Republic of Hakasia.
In a city with 15,000 inhabitants, there will be a special legal regime for entrepreneurship, as well as a minimum amount of capital investment by residents and a minimum number of new permanent jobs.
This is expected to attract about 2.5 billion rubles of investment into the city, as well as more than 600 new jobs.
The list of economic activities in which the Abasa TMA will have a special legal regime for business activities includes, for example, crop production, livestock production, food production, non-alcoholic beverages and clothing.
Already, the Government has signed framework agreements for eight investment projects.
It is also planned to reduce the Territory's dependence on the Abakan Mines Enterprise.
In January 2017, the authorities in the region reported that Hakasia had met all the conditions of the Ministry of Economic Development for the establishment of a DOT.
The authorities of the Orenburg region have done the same.
There, the city of Novotroitzk will also have an area ahead of economic and social development.
This will diversify the economy of the monocities, reduce their dependence on the Ural Steel Enterprise, create more than 2.3 thousand jobs and attract more than 8 billion rubles in investment.
The list of economic activities in which the new DOT will have a special legal regime for entrepreneurs includes, inter alia, freshwater fish farming, feed production, medicines and medical materials.
==History==Newtroitzk became the first single town in Orenburg province to be granted the status of a TOR.
It should be recalled that the territory ahead of development is an economic zone with favourable tax conditions, simplified administrative procedures and other privileges that are created to attract investment in improving the lives of the population.
Among the benefits for residents of the LTA are: a profit tax of not more than 5 per cent for the first five years, and not less than 10 per cent for the next five years, social contributions of 7.6 per cent for 10 years, the use of the free customs zone, preferential access to various infrastructure facilities, and preferential rental rates.
